introduction.p:
Consider the vectors
\vvec_1 = \twovec{2}{1}, \vvec_2 = \twovec{1}{2}
in \real^2, which are shown in .

li.p:
We note that
\left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Since there is a pivot position in every row, the span of the vectors is \real^3. Since there is a pivot position in every column, the vectors are linearly independent. Consequently, this set of vectors forms a basis for \real^3.

statement.p:
Notice that the vectors
\evec_1 = \threevec{1}{0}{0}, \evec_2 = \threevec{0}{1}{0}, \evec_3 = \threevec{0}{0}{1}
form the columns of the 3\times3 identity matrix, which implies that this set forms a basis for \real^3. More generally, the set of vectors \evec_1,\evec_2,\ldots,\evec_m forms a basis for \real^m, which we call the standard basis for \real^m. basis, standard

li.p:
If \xvec=\twovec{c_1}{c_2}, we have
\xvec=c_1\vvec_1+c_2\vvec_2 = \left[\begin{array}{rr} 3 \amp 2 \\ -2 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\twovec{c_1}{c_2} = A \coords{\xvec}{\bcal}\text{.}
This matrix A, whose columns are the vectors \vvec_1 and \vvec_2, has a pivot position in every row and every column because the vectors form a basis. It is, therefore, row equivalent to the identity matrix and hence invertible.

 If we define B to be the matrix whose columns
	  are \twovec{1}{2} and \twovec{-2}{1}, then

	    \coords{\xvec}{\bcal} = A^{-1}\xvec =
	    A^{-1}B\coords{\xvec}{\ccal}\text{.} 

	  Therefore,
	  C=A^{-1}B = \left[\begin{array}{rr}
	  -\frac{3}{7} \amp -\frac{4}{7} \\
	  \frac{8}{7} \amp -\frac{1}{7}
	  \end{array}\right]\text{.}

subsection.p:
This activity demonstrates how we can efficiently convert
   between coordinate systems defined by different bases.  Let's
   consider a basis \bcal = \{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_m\}
   and a vector \xvec.  We know that

     \begin{aligned}
     \xvec \amp {}={} c_1\vvec_1 +c_2\vvec_2+\ldots+c_m\vvec_m \\
     \\
     \amp {}={}
     \left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
     \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \cdots \amp \vvec_m
     \end{array}\right]
     \cfourvec{c_1}{c_2}{\vdots}{c_m} \\
     \\
     \amp {}={}
     \left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
     \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \cdots \amp \vvec_m
     \end{array}\right]
     \coords{\xvec}{\bcal}\text{.}
     \end{aligned}

   If we use P_{\bcal} to denote the matrix whose columns are
   the basis vectors, then we find that

     \xvec = P_{\bcal}\coords{\xvec}{\bcal}

   where P_{\bcal} = \left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
   \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \cdots \amp \vvec_m
   \end{array}\right].  This means that the matrix
   P_{\bcal} converts coordinates in the basis \bcal
   into standard coordinates.

Since the columns of P_{\bcal} are the basis vectors
   \vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_m, we know that P_{\bcal}
   \sim I_m, and P_{\bcal} is therefore invertible.
   Since we have

     \xvec = P_{\bcal}\coords{\xvec}{\bcal}
   ,
   we must also have

     P_{\bcal}^{-1}\xvec = \coords{\xvec}{\bcal}
   .

statement.p:
If \bcal is a basis and P_{\bcal} the matrix
whose columns are the basis vectors, then

  \begin{aligned}
  \xvec \amp = P_{\bcal}\coords{\xvec}{\bcal}, \\ \\
  \coords{\xvec}{\bcal} \amp = P_{\bcal}^{-1}\xvec.
  \end{aligned}
